.TH _printf 1 "25/11/2024" "version 1.0" "user commands"
.SH NAME
_printf \- format and print data
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B \fB_printf\fR FORMAT [ARGUMENT]...
.PP
.B \fB_printf\fR OPTION
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The \fB_printf\fR command is used to format and display text and numbers with precise formatting control, similar to the _printf function in the C language.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B %c: prints a single character
.TP
.B %s: prints a string of characters
.TP
.B %d: prints a decimal number
.TP
.B %i: prints an integer in base 10
.TP
.B %%: prints a percent sign
.TP
.B %x: prints a number in hexadecimal (lowercase)
.TP
.B %X: prints a number in hexadecimal (uppercase)
.TP
.B %u: prints an unsigned decimal number
.TP
.B %b: prints a number in binary
.TP
.B %r: prints a string in reverse
.TP
.B %p: prints a pointer address
.TP
.B %R: prints string with rot13
.TP
.B %r: prints string in reverse
.TP
.B %o: prints number in octal
.TP

.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
.B # Example for %c
.nf
_printf("Character: %c\\n", 'A');
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %s
.nf
_printf("String: %s\\n", "Hello");
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %d
.nf
_printf("Decimal number: %d\\n", 42);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %i
.nf
_printf("Integer: %i\\n", 123);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %%
.nf
_printf("Percentage sign: %%\\n");
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %x
.nf
_printf("Hexadecimal (lowercase): %x\\n", 255);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %X
.nf
_printf("Hexadecimal (uppercase): %X\\n", 255);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %u
.nf
_printf("Unsigned decimal: %u\\n", 3147483647);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %b
.nf
_printf("Binary: %b\\n", 98);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %r
.nf
_printf("Reversed string: %r\\n", "Hello");
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %p
.nf
_printf("Pointer address: %p\\n", (void *)0x7fff5100b608);
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %R
.nf
_printf("ROT13 string: %R\\n", "Hello");
.fi
.PP
.B # Example for %o
.nf
_printf("Octal: %o\\n", 98);
.fi
.fi
.SH AUTHOR
